"YDNIW"тЙл$,$,$,$,$,@@

  sisobus
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Wind speed shaping the output: same source, two readings.

  Run two ways:

      windy run      examples/gust.wnd    тЖТ  WINDY
      windy run --v0 examples/gust.wnd    тЖТ  ID\0\0\0  (visually "ID")

  How: the strmode segment "YDNIW" pushes 5 codepoints in reverse, so
  'W' lands on top of the stack. Then тЙл raises speed to 2, and the
  second half of the program is a deliberate 1D obstacle course of
  $/, pairs:

      $   DROP    тАФ tosses the top of the stack
      ,   PUT_CHR тАФ pops the top and writes its codepoint as a char

  At speed 2 the IP only lands on every other cell. The layout puts
  every $ on an odd-index cell and every , on an even-index cell, so
  v1 hits all five `,`s and skips all five `$`s, draining the stack
  cleanly into "WINDY". v0 has no speed mechanic тАФ тЙл is unknown, the
  IP advances cell-by-cell, and the alternating $/, sequence drops a
  letter for every one it prints, so the visible part of the output
  collapses to "ID".

  Tick-by-tick (v1.0 default):

    tick  cell        op            speed   stack after            stdout
    ----  ----------  ------------  -----   --------------------   ------
     1    (0)  "      strmode on    1       []                     тАФ
     2    (1)  Y      push 89       1       [89]                   тАФ
     3    (2)  D      push 68       1       [89,68]                тАФ
     4    (3)  N      push 78       1       [89,68,78]             тАФ
     5    (4)  I      push 73       1       [89,68,78,73]          тАФ
     6    (5)  W      push 87       1       [89,68,78,73,87]       тАФ
     7    (6)  "      strmode off   1       (no change)            тАФ
     8    (7)  тЙл      speed += 1    2       (no change)            тАФ
     9    (9)  ,      pop, putc     2       [89,68,78,73]          W
    10    (11) ,      pop, putc     2       [89,68,78]             I
    11    (13) ,      pop, putc     2       [89,68]                N
    12    (15) ,      pop, putc     2       [89]                   D
    13    (17) ,      pop, putc     2       []                     Y
    14    (19) @      HALT          тАФ       []                     тАФ

  Notice that ticks 9тАУ13 advance by 2 columns each: the IP lands on
  columns 9, 11, 13, 15, 17 тАФ exactly the `,` cells. The `$` cells
  at columns 8, 10, 12, 14, 16 are intermediate cells the IP flies
  over without decoding (SPEC ┬з3.7: at speed N, only the destination
  cell decodes).

  Compare v0 (legacy, with --v0):

    tick  cell        op                          stack after        stdout
    ----  ----------  --------------------------  ----------------   ------
    1-7   (0..6)      same strmode build          [89,68,78,73,87]   тАФ
    8     (7)  тЙл      unknown тАФ warned, NOP       (no change)        тАФ
    9     (8)  $      DROP 87                     [89,68,78,73]      тАФ
    10    (9)  ,      pop 73, putc                [89,68,78]         I
    11    (10) $      DROP 78                     [89,68]            тАФ
    12    (11) ,      pop 68, putc                [89]               D
    13    (12) $      DROP 89                     []                 тАФ
    14    (13) ,      pop empty, putc 0           []                 NUL
    15    (14) $      DROP empty                  []                 тАФ
    16    (15) ,      pop empty, putc 0           []                 NUL
    17    (16) $      DROP empty                  []                 тАФ
    18    (17) ,      pop empty, putc 0           []                 NUL
    19    (18) @      HALT                        []                 тАФ

  The trailing @@ is there because the v1 IP halts at column 19 (one
  past column 18) тАФ speed-2 movement from (17) lands on (19). v0
  halts at (18), one cell earlier. Both terminations are clean.

  Things to play with:

    - Replace тЙл with тЙлтЙл to push speed to 3. The IP now lands on
      columns 10, 13, 16, 19, ... none of which carry `,`, so v1
      prints nothing and falls into the trailing `@@`.

    - Add a тЙк between two of the `,`s. At speed 2 the IP lands on
      тЙк, drops to speed 1, and starts traversing every cell again
      тАФ half the output is "WINDY"-style sampled, half is v0-style
      "$,$,$,..." mangled.

    - Trace it under `windy debug` (v1 default) and watch the
      `speed` row in the state panel jump from 1 to 2 the moment
      the IP visits тЙл. With --v0 the speed row vanishes тАФ there's
      no such concept in legacy mode.
